{
  "duration": 89.12,
  "text": "In real chemistry, you almost never have perfect amounts of both reactants. One runs out first. That's the limiting reagent. Think of it like making sandwiches. Two slices of bread plus one slice of cheese makes one sandwich. If you have ten slices of bread and three slices of cheese, cheese runs out first. Cheese is the limiting reagent. You make three sandwiches, not five. Same in chemistry. Take magnesium plus hydrochloric acid. Mg plus 2 Hce arrow. Mgce 2 plus H2. If you have 2.4 grams of Mg and 100 cM cubed of one molar Hce. Who runs out first? Moles of Mg. 2.4 over 24 equals 0.1 moles. Moles of Hce. Concentration times volume equals 1.0 times 0.1 equals 0.1 moles. The ratio says 1 mg needs 2 Hcl. So 0.1 mg needs 0.2 Hcl. But we only have 0.1. Hcl is the limiting reagent. Now, percentage yield. Theoretical yield is what you should get. Actual yield is what you actually get. Percentage yield equals actual. Over theoretical times 100. If you never get 100%, don't worry. Nobody does. That's real chemistry.",
